I‚Äôve always stressed this. Great designers don‚Äôt just design.‚Å£
-‚Å£
They solve customer and business problems. For one to do so effectively, they need to understand all the moving parts that come into play.‚Å£
-‚Å£
There are 3 main stages when it comes to the business life cycle.‚Å£
-‚Å£
PRE-VALIDATION: An idea that is floating around. The main focus is to launch a MVP as soon as possible to test the market. ‚Å£
PRODUCT MARKET FIT: People show interest. The idea has been launched and you have customers who ‚Äòrepeatedly‚Äô pay you for the value. ‚Å£
SCALE: Your product has proven to retain users, customers are passing on the good word about your service and the businesses core focus is to scale their acquisition channels.‚Å£
-‚Å£
Problems and challenges customers and businesses face during these stages are significantly different. Designers need to adapt to these situations and empathise effectively. ‚Å£
-‚Å£
Here are 5 non-design books to help you build a better understanding of other relevant disciplines:‚Å£
-‚Å£
1. The Lean Startup: Truly understand how fast growing tech startups are now building products. Lean and extremely outcomes driven.‚Å£
2. Made to Stick: Learn how and why some brands and marketing ideas really stick and become viral.‚Å£
3. Good to Great: Understand the fundamental catalysts that drive a business to go from ‚Äògood‚Äô to ‚Äògreat‚Äô.‚Å£
4. Cross the Chasm: Technology adoption is broken up into 5 segments, Innovators, Early adopters, Early Majority, Late Majority and Laggards. Learn what it takes for a product to penetrate the wider audience in today‚Äôs world.‚Å£
5. Emotional intelligence (Harvard business review): In the end it doesn‚Äôt matter how great we are at problem solving, if people don‚Äôt enjoy working with us it means nothing. Understand what it means to have high EQ. This book is a great overview on the impact of EQ on job performance, leadership potential, entrepreneurship, and employability.‚Å£

When I started my company, Design Cuts, we invested an afternoon to define our audience. One of the smartest decisions we could have made.
-
We drew a figure, and called him 'Timmy'. We started by defining 'hard metrics'. Like what Timmy did for a living. How much he earned. What skills he had. What software he used.
-
We took the time to define 'soft metrics'. What did Timmy get excited about? What did Timmy find funny? What hobbies did he have? What was his personality like? This may sound trivial, but combined, they create a rich audience persona.
-
Imagine we got it wrong and created 'Corporate Carl'. A ruthless career climber, chasing materialistic pursuits. He's eats at fancy restaurants and drinks at fancy bars. He's not very empathetic. He's kind of a dick!
-
Instead, we knew our audience persona was: A full time creative. Had enough disposable income to invest in assets to help their work. Empathetic. Resistant to traditional corporate culture. Family orientated. Super geeky about design. Drank a lot of coffee. Slightly geeky. Engaged in creative pursuits outside of design. And hundreds of other traits!
-
It may sound abitrary, and to an extent it is, but this is not about exact science, it's about direction. Not every audience member mapped to this profile, but it was surprising how we attracted people in those early days who were very similar to it. The outcome? When we posted funny designer memes about coffee, they blew up! When we shared our geeky traits and family values, our audience seriously connected. When we talk about the trials and tribulations of being a full-time designer, people feel like we're in their heads.
-
The big takeaway. Creating a good audience persona will: -
Better inform your marketing efforts
-
Make content creation easier
-
Make copywriting easier
-
Make your audience feel understood
-
Create a deeper bond with your audience
-
Let me know in the comments: what do you know about YOUR audience?
-

Want to make more money doing what you do? Try using Price Anchors. The principle is that we all rely too much on the first piece of information that we receive. So when it comes to pricing, anchor high. Say a big number first. This number is usually considerably higher than the number you intend to say.

Here‚Äôs an example of how we use it. I will often tell clients that our minimum level of engagement is $100k. This is regardless of what the task is.

Once we start talking about their goals, motivations and determine what they need, they have been conditioned to think it will cost around 100k. So any number I say that is around $100k will seem very reasonable.

Conversely if the client says they only have $30k before I have the opportunity to bring up the budget, now, I‚Äôm stuck thinking about a number that‚Äôs not too far away from $30k. See how anchors work? Give it a try. When you‚Äôre successful, just remember where you learned this from.

If you‚Äôre not confident talking about money, I recommend using precise numbers. The client will think you really put thought into it. When you become more confident use round numbers for the exact opposite reason. It says to the client ‚Äúit‚Äôs the price if you want to me.‚Äù They can‚Äôt detect a formula to negotiate against.

If you want more, I‚Äôll be doing workshops on Pricing Strategies. Check the last slide for dates. Check the Futur‚Äôs FB page for more info.

So we see these terms floating about on job boards, bios, descriptions, etc. you name it. Everyone is talking about being a product designer, ux designer, or any other of the hot titles focused around design
-
But what the heck is the difference?
-
Product Designers - A Product Designer, according to uxdesign.cc, Design will not be just about users. It will also be about the business. As Product Designers, we must drive product solutions that service the goals of both the users and the company
-
Product Designers are well-versed in many areas and generally oversee the entire lifecycle of a product
-
Think UX Designer meets Product Manager
-
UX Designer - A UX Designer is someone who makes products easy to use. They incorporate user research, understand user behavior, and the target market, and craft solutions for those specific use cases
-
In short, UX Designers are responsible for crafting intuitive and engaging experiences

The power of White Space in UI design -
By: @_ayushjangra_
-
‚ÄúLet‚Äôs reduce the empty space a little so that we present the user with more content at once.‚Äù - The Client
-
How many of you have heard this line from your clients.
-
Clients usually argue and push the tendency that we should condense the content by reducing the negative space with the idea that we are presenting the user with more valuable content at once. Showing more content in one view doesn‚Äôt necessarily accomplish that. That is the myth of ‚Äúless scrolling‚Äù. By giving the UI elements more space, we, as designers, contribute to the emotional aspect of the user experience. We add more breathing space in the UI and relax the overall interaction of the user‚Äôs experience with the UI.
-
Spacing makes the UI breathe and the user feels more comfortable exploring it.
-

App or Website: which to build first?
-
Should you build an app or website first for your startup?
-
This question comes up a lot in the startup world, and there's reasons why I would lean one way over the other in various circumstances. Below I'll give you the pros and cons for going with web over app and vice versa. - 
Website pros:
1. Faster (cheaper) to implement
2. Compatibility
3. Search Engine Optimization
-
Website cons:
1. No offline access
2. Native device limitations
3. Often a clunkier user experience -
App pros:
1. Richer User Experience
2. Native features 
3. Performance
4. Offline access
-
App cons:
1. Development costs
2. Time intensive
3. Maintenance and updates
-
In short, do your research. -

Today I want to talk about a principle in UX called Occam‚Äôs Razor - -
---------------
---------------
üî™This Law States:
--------------
-------------
ü§î When presented with competing hypothetical answers to a problem, select the one with the fewest assumptions.
---
---
üö´ Now..
---
---
üì±Some think this law has to do with simplification in the User Interface (UI). ---
--
----
‚ö†Ô∏èThat is a misconception
--------
--
‚ùìIt‚Äôs about choosing the simplest solution to a problem.
------------
----
ü§öHold up Miriam, you just said it‚Äôs not about simplifying???
---
---------
üëåOkay, to clarify:

______
________
üîé1. Don‚Äôt go for the default solution, spend time researching the best UI pattern to use.
-
-
- Instead of using radio btns for 2 options, try using a switch
---
--
üíª 2. Get out of Sketch! Think about your users mindset & jobs to be done
-
- Ride apps traditionally ask for your current location. But the user mindset is ‚ÄòI need to go somewhere‚Äô How about we ask for the destination first?
---
---
üì±3. Take into consideration how screens are getting bigger & challenge it.
-
- On desktop, the search bar is at the top. When going mobile we just copied this, no questions asked. The bottom of the screen has now become prime real estate, due to thumb reach. Let's bring 'search' down, using a iOS UI pattern - ‚Äòbottom sheets‚Äô

_________
__________
üî≤ There is simplification in terms of taking away elements or white space.
-
üëâ Occam‚Äôs Razor is really about selecting the solution to a problem that is the simplest.

MVP: Minimum Viable Product
It refers to a product development approach where the product is released when it has all the features to satisfy the early adopters. The final, complete set of features is only designed and developed after considering feedback from the product's initial usersÔªø. You can define the most valuable features by conducting research, and analysing the data with user journey maps and using the prioritization matrix. 
For a successful MVP you need to make a difference between what the user WANTS and what the user NEEDS
.

‚Å£
‚Å£

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Å£

‚Å£
üí°Make sure to be relevant to this audience. If a developer talks to designers about his ¬´design¬ª, there is a chance that designers would not get it. ‚Å£

5 steps of UX Design

Define
A good place to start is asking yourself ‚ÄòWhat can we do to improve this problem?‚Äô. You‚Äôll want to identify patterns, pain points, observe customer interactions, and use cases for that particular issue.

Research
After we gather all sorts of info on the problem, we need to start defining our customers. We should map out their social behaviors, demographics, motivations for using a product or service, and their expectations.

Analyze
Now is the time to put all of your ideas to a sketch board and let the creativity flow. Centered around this problem, no idea is off the table. This phase is about generating solutions to problems. 
Design
Concepting, wire framing, prototyping, and creating flows are completed in this step. The goal is to build and implement those solutions discussed in the first step and provide the high fidelity visuals for real-world feedback. 
Test
Here is where we get to validate our designs and research. We‚Äôll gather feedback and analyze those results. If necessary, we‚Äôll return to step 1 and repeat the process until Product Market Fit is achieved.

Every Step Counts‚†Ä

In the last couple of weeks I've worked with @morejanda , the author of Burn your portfolio. Great book by the way, check it out! We tried to define the meaning behind UX and UI design and the relationship between the two. Of course these two are broad categories, so we also focused on their main components. I think this turned out to be a great and simple visualization of what User Experience Design means. I'll share two more series from our collaboration in the following days but until then: Let's dig in!
.
‚ö´ User Experience Design (UX): The experience that a person has as they interact with a product. UX is an umbrella term that encompasses all of the other types of design to create a user‚Äôs experience with a company, product, or service.
.
‚ö´ User Interface Design (UI): The look and feel of a product designed to enhance the customer experience. UI is an umbrella term that encompasses all of the elements the make up the visual and tactile delivery of a user experience.
.
‚ö´ Content Strategy: Identification of content types and strategy to deliver them to a target audience.
.
‚ö´ Information Architecture (IA): The manner in which content is organized.
.
‚ö´ Interaction Design (IxD): The physical interaction a user has with a product.
.
‚ö´ Motion Design: Utilization of motion to enhance a user experience and delivery of content.
.
‚ö´ Visual Design: The visual representation of a content strategy and information architecture.
.

I usually follow this UX process üëáüèº
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
1. Research
2. Structure
3. Wireframes
4. UI
5. Prototype 
6. Test
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
And I use the following tools for each step of the process:
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
1Ô∏è‚É£ Miro
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I use Miro to collaborate and gather information from different sources.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
It‚Äôs like having a digital whiteboard, you can use it to create User Story Mapping, Mood boards, User Journeys, User Personas, etc., it helps me to have all the information that I need in one place.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
2Ô∏è‚É£ Overflow
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Awesome tool to create beautiful user flows or Site maps.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
It syncs pretty well with Sketch which is great for my workflow. Also, you can use it to build flow charts and other types of charts. I also like that you can share your documents with clients easily with one link.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
3Ô∏è‚É£ Sketch
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Sketch is the app that I use to create wireframes and the UI of every product.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
It allows me to create and easily maintain style guides, all the plugins created by the community around this tool is one of its biggest strengths. It also syncs pretty well with Overflow and Invision.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
4Ô∏è‚É£ InVision + Studio
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I use invision to build the prototype that is going to be tested with users.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I also upload to Invision all the designed screens to receive feedback and I use Studio to make animations and clearly communicate ideas to developers which I think is very important.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
5Ô∏è‚É£ Usertesting.com
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
User Testing is the tool I use to test the UI and get feedback from users.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I like this tool because I can have feedback from users really fast, it is easy to set up and it let me target users from almost everywhere and uncover usability issues easily.

It‚Äôs the only way they can survive the extreme conditions they face during their incredible reproduction cycle on the sea ice off Antarctica. During mid-winter blizzards, when males balance the eggs on their feet to keep them off the ice, temperatures can drop to -70 degrees. When I made this image I was standing on top of a platform perched at the edge of a colony and I had to stay still to avoid spooking the birds. It was an ordeal, and it took quite a while before I got warm again, but the images were worth it. Video by @bertiegregory | A group of king penguins run away from an angry bull elephant seal at St Andrews Bay. This beach on the island of South Georgia in the South Atlantic Ocean is known as one of the busiest on the planet as it hosts over 150,000 breeding pairs of king penguins. Their commute from the colony to the sea involves dodging many of these massive elephant seals. Shot as part of a new online series for National Geographic coming soon. Understanding the busines is key to solve business design problem, before understanding completly, DON'T START project.

2. Create UX Process
Every single have different approch and process to solve problems like redesign website or creating new app. Choose right approach accroding to time, budget and requirments.

3. User centred design
User center design is great way to approach and solve design for for end users. and you can start with Persona, User Stories, Secnarios (User cases).

In the heart of Chengdu you can find Du Fu's Thatched Cottage. This 24-acre park and museum was preserved in honour of the Tang Dynasty poet Du Fu. In 1961 the Chinese government established Du Fu Cao Tang as a National Heritage site. Du Fu is one of the most famous and beloved poets in Chinese history, he lived in the cottage with his family and composed 240 poems during his time there.  Inside the gardens are quiet; streams wind through the bamboo shoots and classical architectural styles bring you a strong cultural atmosphere.

One of my favorite things to do at Bryce Canyon National Park is to stand at one of the rim-top overlooks (Bryce Viewpoint, in this case) at sunrise or sunset with a long telephoto lens and pick out interesting features of the hoodoos to photograph. It's an exercise that could keep me happily occupied for hours on end, as the different shapes, textures, and formations of the hoodoos are infinitely fascinating to me. This sunrise was a particularly beautiful, windy, and frigid one. Bryce is up around 8000 feet in elevation and we were there in late November, which makes for freezing temps. But that doesn't matter...it is an amazing sight no matter when you go.

Bryce Canyon National Park (53 of 59)

Creepily clever new painting from Casey Weldon @caseyweldon for his debut solo exhibition with Thinkspace. 'Sentimental Deprivation' is set to open this coming Saturday, June 3 with a reception from 6-9PM.
‚Ä¢
Weldon's works alternate between moments of intense darkness and incandescent light, figuratively and literally. Saturated with lush color and detail, they are stylized by idiosyncratic palette choices that capture a range of brightness and atmosphere, from the intensity of neon to the lambent of dusk and the recesses of twilight obscurity. The unexpected is always at play in the subject matter, as unlikely pairings, exaggerated spatial relationships, and incongruous contexts offer infinite possible realities and suggestive collusions. The world, delivered through the lens of Weldon‚Äôs imagination, is distorted on a hyperbolic visual plane, where the mythic proportions of incidental symbolism are laid open to the willing. Weldon creates works with hooks rather than imperatives, providing an openness to interpretation for the viewer rather than a prescriptive demand to be read.

Photo by @shonephoto (Robbie Shone) with words by adventure writer and presenter @CharlieBoscoe - Imagine being tasked with the job of getting thousands of soldiers safely across this terrain out of sight from the enemy. That was the challenge faced by military commanders as battles raged across the Dolomites during the First World War. The solution they came up with was nothing short of ingenious; make the mountains climbable and accessible to troops using cables, wires and metal rungs. Those "via ferratas" (iron roads) are still in place and now lead climbers and mountaineers to some of the greatest summits in the Alps.

If life is all about perspective then the Alaskan landscape by air should be a prerequisite for anyone looking for deeper meaning. Every time I fly here I see things I have never seen before. In many ways the finest example of art in nature you can witness.
.
The best part is almost everyone owns a plane so flying is actually affordable. For more from this series & what I shot it with check my IG story.
